Anonymous Mon 06 Jun 2022 14:18:41 No.48311753 Report
Quoted By: >>48311768
>>48309426
>Review for Toons in Tinseltown (Ch1 & Ch2)

It's a very good read and I can't wait to see more.

The description is great, the world building is well shown and I really want to see more. Especially in how toons go about business Hollywood style, maybe leaning into the darker aspects of Hollywood and the film industry.

The best part to me is Anon's inner dialogue. The way it captures his emotions is suburb and does really well to reveal a nervous man who, while not a complete wimp, is still new to the high life.

One glaring issue I have is the name of 'Anon Imos'.

It feels really out of place. The name 'Anon' to me is more suited for short form texts and I feel this story should go with a named protagonist instead. He really stands out amongst the other well-defined and described characters that it just feels off. Especially because he has a defined backstory and character. (this is a problem for many hmofa stories)

I also think you could lean into the 'toon' aspect a bit more, kind of like in Roger Rabbit. But, seeing how Anon walks a pink panther around, it's getting there.

Overall, good job. I'm excited to see more.

There are a couple of factors at work. The first is, yes, you're getting old. You have by and large discovered what you like and where to get it, so you go looking a little less. I recognize the thing because it's from a game a YouTuber I watch has played. But I have failed to identify other pop culture things, sometimes quite old, because I simply never get into contact with the subcultures they're from.

Secondly, there are more people using the internet than ever. If you're actually somewhat old, and not just some mid-20's dude beginning to feel the first pangs of age, you remember a time when the internet was truly a niche thing. That is to say, optional. Entire segments of society never used it. The people who did use it were nerds, and they've been gradually pushed to the side by utter normies. And you probably think normies suck (and you're right).

Thirdly, well, yes. The corps have largely figured things out, and while the internet has grown, the dedicated internet seems to have shrunk. How often do you go to some proprietary site for something? Pretty much never, right? It's all hubs and social networks. As corpo internet expertise has grown, the expertise of the userbase has diminished. Remember hearing those stories about how some schoolboy made a useful site and raked in the cash? That shit doesn't happen anymore. The last thing of its kind was Bitcoin, and they're still fuming over that one. Worse, Western governments have also taken an interest in the internet, and while they claim to fight corporate control, they inject their own every time they do so.
